; DECISIONS.decision-log.udon
; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; The running log of settled calls for vivarium — the PRIOR that TODO.md
; leans on ("given these decisions, here is the work"; "here is work pending
; decision X"). Started 2026-07-12 at Joseph's direction. This is a first-pass
; schema; it will evolve. Readers must ignore fields they do not recognize.
;
; FAST-APPEND, INTERLEAVE-FREE (the convenience property we actually want):
;   This is a WORKING DOCUMENT, not an immutable ledger. The one property we
;   preserve is that an agent can APPEND a new decision cheaply (e.g. `>>`)
;   WITHOUT first reading the file, and concurrent appends don't garble:
;   • Each |decision is a SELF-CONTAINED, TOP-LEVEL block (starts at column 0).
;     There is NO wrapping parent element — so a new entry is appended at EOF
;     with no need to read, parse, or re-close anything above it.
;   • Append the whole block in ONE write, preceded by a single blank line.
;     O_APPEND makes a single write() atomic on POSIX, so concurrent agents
;     cannot interleave entries. Keep a block small enough to be one write.
;   • EDITING existing entries IS allowed — refine, correct, re-flow freely.
;     When a decision is REPLACED you MAY append a new |decision that
;     :supersedes the old slug (history preserved), or you may just edit the
;     entry in place. :supersedes is an available option, not a requirement.
;   • Slugs are unique and kebab-case.
;
; OPEN QUESTION (deliberately undecided for now): whether this file becomes the
;   full HISTORICAL decision log — with a separate projected "open / relevant
;   decisions" view generated off it — OR stays the "open relevant decisions"
;   working set, with historical/superseded items swept out into a separate
;   trace file. Not settled; do not assume either policy.
;
; ENTRY SHAPE (compacted 2026-07-12 — a whole decision reads in a few lines):
;   • HEADER LINE carries the slug and the four fixed fields inline, in order:
;       |decision[kebab-slug] :date YYYY-MM-DD :by <auth> :status <s> :topic <t>
;   • METADATA LINE(S), indented, one field per line: :session (always) and any
;     bespoke :-metadata such as :supersedes <slug>. :session is redundant while
;     every entry is from one session, but it is carried on every entry so the
;     ledger stays sortable/attributable once that stops being true.
;   • STATEMENT: the decision itself, written as the entry's PLAIN BODY TEXT (not
;     a labeled sub-field — that read cleanest, so it is the standing choice), on
;     ONE logical line. See the no-column-wrap rule below.
;   • |reason — the reasoning / context (renamed from |why).
;     |impact — the work it implies (renamed from |does; mirror into TODO if not
;     immediate). Their text sits INLINE right after the field name when it is
;     under ~120 chars; otherwise on the following indented line. |ref (files,
;     commits, LEXICON entries) is kept where present.
;   • NO COLUMN-WRAP: statement / reason / impact / ref are each ONE logical line,
;     never hand-wrapped to a width. Markdown line-breaks are for genuine
;     structure only (lists, tables).
;
; AUTHORITY LEGEND (Joseph's taxonomy, kept honest — do not inflate):
;   joseph — Joseph's call; Claude ABSTAINED: offered no strong position, or it
;            is a matter of Joseph's intent / taste / faith to decide.
;   us     — Joint: Joseph decided AND Claude SUSTAINS it on the merits.
;   claude — Claude's own tactical call, logged so it does not fall through the
;            cracks; Joseph may veto or promote it.
; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


|decision[nomos-plural-invariant] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic naming
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The plural of "nomos" is "nomos" (invariant), not "nomoi".
  |reason
    Pronunciation: "nomoi" (NOM-oy) is awkward to say aloud. Cost accepted with open eyes — a mild break from the deliberately-Greek law-article register (the etymological plural IS nomoi), and a singular/plural ambiguity that context resolves (cf. "series", "sheep"). Honest because it is declared here and in the LEXICON rather than left implicit.
  |impact
    Update LEXICON.udon #term[nomos] (":forms pl. nomos, invariant"); sweep the prose "nomoi" -> "nomos" opportunistically. Verified 0 code identifiers named "nomoi", so this is docs-only and cannot break a build. Family words unaffected (nomothete / nomothetic / nomotheke).
  |ref  LEXICON.udon #term[nomos]

|decision[regula-collapses-to-order-and-manifest] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  :supersedes (the regula-keep build-spec in doc/plan/regula-conformance-design.md §5 — that doc stays as the reasoning trail, no longer the plan)
  No `regula` artifact for now. World-level conformance is carried by the ORDINUM (descriptive kind-floor — what the kind requires) + the MANIFEST (per-world prescription — what this world chose: :order, :target-phase, permits, participation), tracked against the nomotheke / tabularium. Reach for an in-between "something" (a regula, or whatever) only if it genuinely gets awkward.
  |reason
    "Don't coin the noun until it earns its keep." The 2026-07-12 declarative-frontier spikes showed the conformance audit needs neither a Slot nor a Regula object — a promise's fluxed-quantity + :kept-by carries what `slot` reached for, and permits live naturally on the manifest.
  |impact
    regula.rs is NOT built. TODO's Regula-Terrestris Slot/Permit/Regula items (2/4/5) are superseded — permits move onto the manifest. Keep the ordinum + the audit; watch for the point where the two-artifact scheme actually strains.
  |ref  doc/plan/regula-conformance-design.md · VIVARIA-DEFINITIONS.md

|decision[core-view-wall-observe-only] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  A VIEW only observes; it never authors world-evolution parameters. The ethereal explorer queries what the world autonomously did — it holds no knob that changes what the world IS.
  |reason
    Founding core/view wall (DESIGN.md), re-asserted after a violation this session: a `VIVARIUM_EROSION_EPOCHS` knob was added to the globe (the view choosing how long the world erodes). "Erode for N epochs" is a world-evolution decision. A view holding it makes the ethereal explorer NON-ethereal — and the milestone is moratorium-clear precisely BECAUSE the observer has no causal access. The knob was reverted.
  |ref  commit 7b65483 (revert)

|decision[debug-poke-then-consolidate] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic process
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Unprincipled interventions WHILE coding/debugging a phenomenon are legitimate — poke, hand-tune, probe to understand. The discipline is the SECOND half: back the poke out and consolidate the gain into the principled framework. A poke left standing (as the answer, or as a view/instrument knob) is the failure, not the poke itself.
  |reason
    Joseph's methodology, stated 2026-07-12. Worked example this session: a hand-passed `uplift 3` in erosion_preview and the globe epochs knob (the pokes) -> both backed out -> uplift consolidated into its own declared nomos (the gain). Instruments MAY poke the kernel; the world path and views may not keep the poke.

|decision[new-system-must-reach-the-goal-not-reimplement-poc] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic process
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The point of "get world-building up to the exploration phase" is to prove the NEW declarative system (nomotheke -> pull-query -> store, composed by the flux web) can reach an eroded/uplifted, explorable world PRINCIPLED-LY — not to re-implement the worldview proof-of-concept (which already makes eroded worlds ad-hoc).
  |reason
    Guards against mistaking motion for progress: porting knobby PoC code into the frame is not the deliverable; a legible, auditable, composed set of nomoi the world evolves itself from — and a view merely observes — is.

|decision[terminology-register-by-layer] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic naming
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Name by layer, honesty above all: (1) ONTOLOGICAL / theoretical terms for the common architecture (the participation ontology, law/nomos, rung, kingdom/estate); (2) SCIENTIFIC / phenomenal / literature terms for the science & algorithms — the nomoi ESPECIALLY (stream-power, drainage, uplift, orography…), preferring the widely-adopted term the subfield's literature uses; (3) standard CODE / tech terms for genuinely fluid implementation concerns (buffers, tiles, GPU kernels). Every word kept HONEST — it must not imply structure, mechanism, or fidelity it lacks.
  |reason
    Joseph's framing, 2026-07-12. This is the governing rule the specific naming calls below (spine, tile, …) are instances of. Register signals layer; a term that crosses registers should notice it is doing so (cf. the Greek-machinery / Latin-governance / plain-English-lived convention already observed).

|decision[spine-nomos-to-initial-topography] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status proposed :topic naming
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Rename the `spine` nomos to `initial-topography` — the standard landscape-evolution-model (LEM) term, immediately legible to geomorphologists with no lexicon entry needed. (First idea was `surface-prior` — its own `system` field — but "prior" is statistical register; Joseph asked for the literature term if one means the same thing, and it does.)
  |reason
    "Spine" is an invented world-backbone metaphor in a nomos (the science layer, per terminology-register-by-layer) and misleads geologically — Joseph: "I don't know what spine is referring to, geologically." The LEM literature is unambiguous: landscape elevation evolves as tectonic-uplift U + diffusion + fluvial erosion (K·A^m|∇h|) acting on an INITIAL TOPOGRAPHY / initial condition. With uplift now its own nomos (uplift-is-its-own-nomos), the extraction clarifies that the spine is precisely that initial-condition surface — not "tectonics". So the rename is doubly honest post-extraction. Our three nomoi now map 1:1 onto the standard LEM: uplift = U, erosion = the K·A^m + creep terms, spine = initial topography.
  |impact
    On confirm: rename the nomos spine-tile -> initial-topography (name + `system` field + version + methods + docs). Re-keys its memos (name is in the store key) — cheap recompute. DEFERRED off Joseph's play session; sweep deliberately. Does NOT decide the "-tile suffix" question (see tile-as-honest-flat-artifact).
  |ref  LEM standard form (Wikipedia "Landscape evolution model"; stream-power + diffusion + uplift U on an initial surface) — web-checked 2026-07-12.

|decision[tile-as-honest-flat-artifact] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic naming
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  "tile" is acceptable as an IMPLEMENTATION-register term for what it actually is today: a flat, memoized, row-major nx×nx region of ONE scalar field at one level (Vec<f32>). Keep the word where the artifact really is a tile; do NOT ban it.
  |reason
    The metaphor is clay-rectangle: flat, four-sided, baked (hard) earth, nominal depth vs width/height, composing to mosaics — which fits a raster field-slice and is standard in the literature. Two guardrails (Joseph, 2026-07-12): (a) a "tile" that FLATTENS AWAY column richness — water-retention down the column, wetness, slope, multiple materials, the precipitation surface — is the failure mode; if an object could be "much more than a tile", it should not be called one. (b) A tile / region / chunk is a legitimate CODED BRIDGE between two of the three primary ontological areas (e.g. erosion-tile as the bridge artifact of the fluvial-erosion nomos), and such bridges — especially performance/GPU-facing ones — will be needed; the subfield's literature is the main clue for the right word, and widely-adopted terms win.
  |impact
    DEFINE `tile` in LEXICON.udon with these explicit limits (one field, flat, at a level; NOT a column/chunk/patch) — its being UNDEFINED is the actual sin, not the word. Distinguish from `chunk` (Hilbert-aligned subdivision) and `patch` (haloed compute array). Keep an antenna for the literature term when a nomos's output grows past a flat field (columns, strata, multi-material). Revisit per nomos.

|decision[uplift-is-its-own-nomos] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The tectonic driver (rock uplift) is its own declared nomos that erosion CONSUMES — not a hidden term inside the erosion kernel. Even a crude 30-line stub (or a no-op) is right, as long as it is separate, declared, and auditable.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "uplift is a separate nomos that right now is 30 lines… or even a no-op." The world grows macro relief only under a tectonic driver; making it a nomos means the flux web shows "erosion consumes rock-uplift-rate <- uplift" and the driver is swappable for the real mantle-thermal source later. LANDED.
  |ref  commit d8a2596 · crates/vivarium-world/src/uplift.rs · TODO §thermal-spine

|decision[flux-web-substrate-on-common-ground] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Built the flux-quantity vocabulary + `consumes` on NomosDecl + the pre-run requisite/conservation audit ahead of, and independent of, the regula question — because both the (then-open) regula options agreed on it. LANDED.
  |reason
    It is the declarative spine the milestone's honesty rests on ("rain without a sky" / "mountains without tectonics" become mechanical audit findings) and it did not require deciding the world-level profile's shape. Tactical, but load-bearing.
  |ref  commit 62ad351 · crates/vivarium-world/src/{flux,audit}.rs

|decision[cli-world-dir-default-and-symlink-promotion] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic tooling
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  `vivarium <cmd> [dir]` — world dir optional, resolving as the globe does (explicit -> $VIVARIUM_WORLD -> ~/.cache/vivarium/globe-world). Promote to system-wide via a symlink into a PATH dir pointing at the release build (~/.local/bin/vivarium -> target/release/vivarium), NOT a cargo-install snapshot.
  |reason
    So `vivarium status` and `vivarium-globe` agree by default, and the installed command tracks rebuilds instead of going stale (~/.cargo/bin is not on Joseph's mise PATH; ~/.local/bin is). Caveat logged: `cargo clean` breaks the symlink.
  |ref  commit (cli world-dir) · TODO §"unify default world dirs" (now addressed)

|decision[probes-before-claims-no-plausibility-as-verification] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic process
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Reaffirmed (Joseph caught a live instance): no physics/behavior claim without its probe. A structurally-plausible statement asserted with verification's authority is the failure to guard against — verify against the actual kernel/run first.
  |reason
    This session: "erosion is invisible at macro scale" was asserted as physics-law; it was a rationalization. The kernel showed the real cause (uplift_m=0, no tectonic driver; L19-tuned params run at L9). The retraction + the uplift nomos followed. Already a standing project norm; logged because it bit this session.

|decision[initial-topography-name-holds] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic naming
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  :supersedes spine-nomos-to-initial-topography
  CONFIRMED: the `spine` nomos becomes `initial-topography`. Weighed Joseph's phase-echo ideas — the ordinum's phase 0 is "ante-mundane", suggesting `ante-topography`, or `mundane` (with eroded as `post-mundane`) — and held the LEM term.
  |reason
    terminology-register-by-layer governs: a NOMOS is the science layer, so it takes the term working geomorphologists read instantly (initial-topography), not an ontological/Latin coinage that would need a lexicon entry (ante-topography / mundane belong to the ORDINUM's register). The phase-echo is real and kept — but at the ordinum layer: phase-0 ante-mundane's surface Promise is :kept-by the initial-topography nomos. The ontological name names the PHASE, the science name names the MECHANISM, and :kept-by is the honest bridge — no register-bleed. Joseph deferred the call ("happy to defer to you"); we align on the principle.
  |impact
    When the rename sweeps: wire ante-mundane -> :kept-by initial-topography in tabularium/terrestris.ordinum.udon. Sweep still queued (see spine-nomos-to-initial-topography |impact).

|decision[water-conserved-from-ante-mundane-mass] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Water is never conjured: the ante-mundane phase declares the fraction of planetary MASS that is chemical water, which fixes a conserved inventory the reservoirs (ocean, atmosphere) merely partition — the honest root beneath "rain".
  |reason  Joseph, 2026-07-12: "tie the atmosphere reservoir back to ante-mundane giving the proportion of actual mass that is chemical water… at least the basics of a global water-cycle conservation." Resolves the "rain from nothing" worry at its root and grounds the audit's precipitation-UNMET in a real conserved source. LANDED as the `hydrosphere` nomos — the framework's first non-field (reservoir/box) representation kind, which also validates that the store/nomotheke/flux-web contract is representation-agnostic (a box keys by identity alone, no spatial coords).
  |impact  hydrosphere.rs + Planet.mass_kg/surface_area + flux ATMOSPHERE_WATER + ASSUMPTIONS (water mass fraction / atmosphere fraction / planet mass); vivarium status prints the budget in real units. Next: ice+groundwater as their own reservoirs (un-lump from ocean) and the climate nomos that consumes atmosphere-water → produces precipitation (the dynamic FLOW), resolving the last audit UNMET. Ante-mundane's water Promise should be :kept-by hydrosphere in the ordinum, alongside initial-topography for surface.
  |ref hydrosphere.rs · ASSUMPTIONS.md · TODO §water-system

|decision[ascii-globe-in-info-colored-by-state] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status wish :topic tooling
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  NULLABLE WISH (a feature to TRY when appropriate, NOT a requirement; drop without guilt if a primitive attempt isn't compelling): render a primitive ASCII/ANSI globe as part of `vivarium info` — a non-animated, non-controllable snapshot projection — coloring regions by what they have reached in SPACE and TIME/PHASE (which detail level / phase is materialized where).
  |reason  Joseph, 2026-07-12 (delighting in the hydrosphere): wants the world's build-state legible AT A GLANCE, geographically. Reference: github.com/adamsky/globe (Rust ASCII globe). Projection: Joseph votes HEALPix (en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HEALPix) UNLESS a projection fitting our cube-sphere / quad-sphere topology makes more sense — our data is native cube-sphere CellId, so an orthographic-from-space or an equal-area cube-sphere-native projection may map our cells more faithfully than reprojecting onto HEALPix. Existing starting points: the `globe_ascii` example (orthographic ASCII land/sea over the store) and spikes/globe (Bevy).
  |impact  Delegated a primitive attempt 2026-07-12. Belongs to the broader `vivarium info` legibility work (register-separated, unit-bearing world report; level→metres, tiles→%-of-planet).

|decision[seam-grid-leads-snyder-healpix] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status lead :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  RESEARCH LEAD for the seam problem (the highest-leverage truth-improvement, per Joseph): equal-area sphere pixelizations may reduce the distortion that makes face-edge / cross-tile seams prominent. Investigate when the seam becomes the focus — NOT a decision to switch grids.
  |reason  Joseph, 2026-07-12: "HEALPix and Snyder Equal-Area Cubed Spheres offer mathematically rigorous, distortion-free vertex distributions." Snyder's equal-area cubed sphere sits directly on our topology (a cube-sphere with equal-area cells); our current cube-sphere projection has non-uniform cell area + face-edge distortion, which is part of what the seam fix must reconcile (seam_ridge: real ratio 2.45–5.79, growing with the age gap — NOT the "22888" this entry originally cited, which was a divide-by-zero; see `seam-probes-were-measuring-seabed`). An equal-area base grid could make cross-face / cross-tile flux matching more uniform (less distortion to reconcile at the boundary). HEALPix is the other rigorous option but re-pixelizes away from the cube-sphere — the globe agent's reason to avoid it for RENDERING stands; for the SEAM it's a base-grid question with a different tradeoff.
  |impact  Weigh during the seam work (doc/theory/multiscale-seams.md). Refs: Snyder 1992 (equal-area cubed sphere); Górski et al. 2005 (HEALPix).

|decision[climate-nomos-closes-the-flux-web] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Precipitation is the conserved atmosphere reservoir's THROUGHPUT: precip = atmosphere stock ÷ residence time. This is the flow that makes the hydrosphere a cycle, and it CLOSES the declared flux web — every consumed quantity now has a producer ("unmet flux needs: none").
  |reason  Following the ordinum at the lowest honest epistemic tier Joseph named — "mechanically sufficient, doesn't violate causation or conservation, but not yet true to anything else". It is conserving (precip = evaporation in steady state, so the inventory is untouched), causal (rain scales with the stock), and order-correct BY CONSTRUCTION (~25 mm atmosphere over a ~9-day residence = ~1 m/yr, which is Earth's mean precipitation) — better than merely mechanically-sufficient, without pretending to a researched climate model. It is also the first BOX → FIELD coupling (a reservoir feeding a field through the store), extending the representation-agnostic proof. HONEST LIMIT, declared: v0 is globally UNIFORM — no ITCZ, orography, or latitude bands — so a *pattern* claim from this precipitation would be false; only its global mean is meant.
  |impact  climate.rs + CLIMATE nomos; erosion consumes precip as a relative discharge WEIGHT (uniform → 1.0 → behaviour-preserving, and it responds to geography for free once climate has any); water rains the principled rate. The old ~9000× "rain rate" fudge is DECOMPOSED: rain is now principled, and only a declared `bounded-fill acceleration` remains (retired by the analytic hydrological init). NEXT RUNG: give climate geography (insolation + spin→circulation bands + orography). 81/81 green.
  |ref climate.rs · nomotheke.rs · ASSUMPTIONS.md (atmosphere residence time / bounded-fill acceleration) · TODO §water-system

|decision[seam-probes-were-measuring-seabed] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic process
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The fluvial unit tests and `seam_ridge` ran on a 100%-SUBMARINE footprint (165_800, 413_600 @ L19 = 3709–3715 m, below SEA_LEVEL_M 4000), where every cell is an outlet, so incision/deposition/drainage all no-op (max|Δh| after 80 epochs = 0.000 m, bit-exactly). The tests passed by comparing no-ops; `seam_ridge`'s famous "ratio 22888" was `0 ÷ 1e-9` — a divide-by-zero against the epsilon floor. FIXED: probes moved to verified land (108_500, 186_350 @ L19, relief 5072–5216 m) + a `test_footprint_is_actually_land` guard so a future prior change cannot silently drown them again.
  |reason  THE SEAM HAD NEVER BEEN MEASURED. The real ratio is **2.45 (18e) / 3.76 (60e) / 5.79 (150e)** — four orders of magnitude below the phantom, and it says something true: it GROWS with the differential age gap while the interior stays flat (0.079→0.103), which is exactly the mean-pin conserving block means but not boundary gradients. This independently corroborates the honest 2026-07-03 measurement in DESIGN-SYSTEMS (4.3×/5.3×/7.1×), i.e. the probe once worked and later regressed when its footprint drowned.
  |impact  METHODOLOGICAL, and the real lesson: **an alarming number that CONFIRMS your prior gets less scrutiny than a boring one.** 22888 "proved" the seam was broken, which is what everyone already believed, so nobody divided it back out. The tell was printed every run — the ratio was bit-identical across all three age gaps swept, which no real physical measurement would be. Claude repeated it as evidence three times, and twice rationalised a bit-exact zero elsewhere (seam_ridge's epoch-invariance; uplift=0's unchanged relief) instead of asking why it was exactly zero. Standing guard: a probe that cannot fail is not a probe. Check that the physics can even EXECUTE at the probe's footprint before trusting its number.
  |ref erosion.rs fluvial_tests::small + test_footprint_is_actually_land · examples/seam_ridge.rs · ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md §0.1 · doc/design/DESIGN-SYSTEMS.md (the 2026-07-03 honest measurement)

|decision[snyder-closes-the-projection-lead] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  KEEP the equiangular cube-sphere and CellId; change the KERNELS, not the grid. The equal-area lead (Snyder / HEALPix) closes — negatively, on numbers from the primary source.
  |reason
    Snyder 1992 Table 1 (primary, supplied by Joseph): for the CUBE, equal-area gives max angular deformation ω = 25.17°, scale factors a = 1.248 / b = 0.801 → **1.56× shape distortion** (a·b ≈ 1, confirming equal-area). Set that against grid_lab's measurement: finite-volume conserves EXACTLY (~1e-15) on our NON-equal-area grid, while isotropy error (1.16–1.25× near corners) does NOT converge away with refinement. So **conservation is a SCHEME property (FV fixes it on any grid) and shape/isotropy is a GRID property (no scheme fixes it)** — which means equal-area trades away the thing we already fix for free, to worsen the one thing we cannot fix at all. Wrong trade. Also from Table 1: the cube is a genuinely POOR polyhedron (ω 25.17°) next to the truncated icosahedron (ω 3.75°, scale variation <3.3%) — but hexagons/pentagons do not subdivide into four, and quadtree-ability is what our whole CellId/LOD architecture rests on. The real tension is therefore quadtree-ability vs base-polyhedron quality, a much later and bigger question than any projection tweak.
  |impact
    Do the finite-volume + metric work (projection-independent, fixes what is wrong TODAY). A full measured comparison (Snyder + HEALPix + a geodesic/hexagonal "odd one") is delegated → `ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md`, so future readers with DIFFERENT algorithms can read off THEIR metrics rather than inherit our conclusion.
  |ref Snyder 1992 Cartographica 29(1) 10–21 Table 1 · examples/grid_lab.rs · ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md

|decision[corner-pathology-is-a-diagonal-artifact] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The valence-3 corner pathology is an artifact of MFD's 8-neighbour fan, NOT of the sphere. Reformulate routing as gradient-projected EDGE flux and the 24 defective cells largely stop being special.
  |reason
    Joseph named the pathology exactly: at a corner your up-neighbour's left edge is welded to your left-neighbour's top edge — the diagonal cell does not exist. But true finite-volume flux crosses EDGES; diagonals share only a vertex (zero-length edge) and carry no flux. `water.rs` is already 4-edge flux form (fl/fr/ft/fb) and would simply have 3 edges at a corner, conserving exactly — NOTHING special happens. Only `erosion.rs`'s MFD needs the diagonal that isn't there, and its diagonals are themselves a hack against grid-aligned bias (its own comment says so). Routing by projecting the local gradient onto each real edge normal, weighted by edge length (D-∞ generalised to a mesh), needs no diagonals, works at ANY valence, conserves by construction, and removes grid bias more honestly than the diagonal hack did.
  |impact
    If it holds, the seam work is not "hand-derive stencils for the weird classes" but "stop using a stencil that needs cells the sphere doesn't have". PROVE IT before acting: build the corner topology (three faces meeting) and show edge-flux routing closes at valence 3 where 8-neighbour MFD cannot. Erosion's routing is then the single kernel that must change.

|decision[geometric-contract-metric-set] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  Every algorithm carries an IMPLICIT geometric contract — the properties it silently assumes its cells guarantee. Declare them, as we already declare magic constants (ASSUMPTIONS) and flux needs (consumes). The unit is the STENCIL, not the cell.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: naive "tiles" were not affording these. The full set: cell area · edge length · **centre-to-mid-edge arm** (the correct FV gradient arm — when centre-line and edge normal aren't collinear, the difference IS the non-orthogonality correction) · angle/non-orthogonality · **valence / number-of-sides** · the **joint stencil geometry** (a flux across edge (i,j) needs the neighbour's numbers too, and the configurations cluster into ~10 congruence classes) · **curvature, SPLIT IN TWO** — "flat-via-gravity" (the surface is a gravitational equipotential, so water locally experiences a flat plane, which is exactly why shallow-water's flat assumption is legitimate) vs arc/metric geometry in the embedding (distances, areas, transport at large spans); Joseph's gloss: "geometry in euclidean space vs geometry in einstein spacetime" — a grid can be fine for one and wrong for the other · **strata volumes** (the shell's volume element scales as r², ~0.6% over our 20 km shell — a MASS term, and rock mass is what erosion must conserve).
  |impact
    Split DISCRETE configuration class (finite, ~10, a cheap branch — dispatches the code path) from CONTINUOUS metrics (analytic in position). That answers the innermost-loop cost properly: branch once on class, evaluate metrics analytically — no neighbour table, no 8–16× memory. Then nomos-declares-what-it-needs / grid-declares-what-it-provides / audit-matches, exactly like the flux web, with grid_lab supplying the magnitude of each violation. ALSO: weight SEQUENCING above isotropy when judging grids — Priority-Flood and drainage accumulation are globally ORDERED (elevation-sorted, strictly downstream), so a seam can put a cell's downstream neighbour in another partition and SERIALISE the sweep. Diffusion is embarrassingly parallel and therefore the least informative test.

|decision[declared-ocean-does-not-fit-the-generated-basins] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  MEASURED CONTRADICTION: the conserved ocean the hydrosphere derives (1.3735e9 km³) does NOT FIT the terrain the spine generates. Basin capacity, filled to the planet's highest peak, is 1.3619e9 km³ — ratio 1.01×. Derived sea level lands 23 m ABOVE the highest ground: land fraction 0.0%, a total water-world. The 33.4% land we have been building and eroding exists ONLY because SEA_LEVEL_M was decreed (4000 m, arbitrary) rather than derived.
  |reason
    Two things declared INDEPENDENTLY and never reconciled: the water inventory (earth-ref, conserved, from the ante-mundane mass fraction) and the surface relief (arbitrary fBm bands, ASSUMPTIONS "continental band" ±1500 m). Found by the standing discipline — make a DECREED thing DERIVABLE and see if it coheres. Same species as "rain without a sky". The margin is the tell: 1.01×, not 10× — so the total RELIEF (~3.7 km) is roughly the right scale; what is wrong is the DISTRIBUTION. fBm is UNIMODAL, so there are no deep basins to hold the water and no high platforms to stand above it (the "drowned sponge" the hypsometry probe's own docstring named). Earth holds the same ocean AND keeps 29% land only because its hypsometry is BIMODAL — abyssal plains ~−4.5 km, continental platforms ~+0.5 km — and that bimodality is ISOSTASY: two crust types of different density floating at different heights (light granitic continental rides high, dense basaltic oceanic sits low).
  |impact
    **Bimodality is not a fidelity upgrade — it is the physical precondition for land existing at all.** TODO's "Prior v3 — two-mode crustal prior" is promoted from nice-to-have to a HARD COHERENCE REQUIREMENT: as declared, this world cannot exist. Next: a crust-type field (continental vs oceanic) with isostatic heights derived from density, replacing the single-population fBm; THEN sea level becomes a derived nomos consuming the ocean stock + hypsometry (retiring SEA_LEVEL_M, the arbitrary datum that also drowned our test footprints for months). Probe: examples/sea_level_probe.rs (true spherical per-cell areas; Σ solid angle self-tested against 4π).
  |ref examples/sea_level_probe.rs · ASSUMPTIONS.md (SEA_LEVEL_M / continental band / planetary water inventory) · TODO §Prior v3 · ref/research/early-continents-survey.md §6 (target: land 2–15%)

|decision[water-world-is-the-promise-not-the-bug] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic physics
  :supersedes declared-ocean-does-not-fit-the-generated-basins
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  CORRECTION. The sea_level_probe measurement stands; my reading of it was BACKWARDS. A submerged, 0%-land world is not a contradiction — it is the ordinum's Phase-1 promise KEPT (`charge[smooth-water-surface]` → `promise[water-covered-surface]`). The BUG is the opposite: `SEA_LEVEL_M = 4000` is MANUFACTURING FORBIDDEN LAND. Abyssal's `charge[emergent-land] :tag gate` says it outright — "meaningful non-volcanic land above sea level — delivered by uplift / proto-tectonic processes, **never an initial condition**."
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "according to the ordinum, land doesn't even rise above the sea at all until somewhere near the beginning of phase 3. Rain starts up etc. while the planet is still covered in water." Verified in tabularium/terrestris.ordinum.udon. So the probe CONFIRMS the ordinum (our conserved inventory can deliver the water-covered surface) and CONVICTS the spine, whose OWN nomos declaration already said so: "phase-structurally it impersonates Abyssal output rather than the Phase-2 submerged promise (Joseph, 2026-07-10)." Our 33.4% of continents is Phase-3 output that was never earned. **BIMODALITY IS NOT A FIX TO THE PRIOR** — isostasy is the MECHANISM by which Abyssal DELIVERS land (crust differentiates, buoyant continental crust rises); it belongs to the emergent-land charge, not to the initial condition. This also recasts the vacuous-test finding: erosion no-op'ing on submarine ground is PHYSICALLY CORRECT — `erosion-carving` is itself a Phase-3 gate charge, and there is nothing to carve until land exists.
  |impact
    CORRECTED ORDER OF WORK. (1) Derive sea level from the hydrosphere's ocean stock → the world becomes correctly SUBMERGED; `SEA_LEVEL_M` retires; the fBm becomes honest BATHYMETRY (seafloor relief) instead of fake continents. (2) ABYSSAL MUST EARN THE LAND — uplift + proto-tectonics + crust differentiation deliver `emergent-land`; **the `uplift` nomos built today is exactly the piece that must do this**. (3) THEN `erosion-carving` begins, on land that was produced rather than assumed. Joseph's standing point holds: fBm/Perlin was never going to give primordial dynamics TO ERODE — at that phase there is nothing to erode; the dynamics must MAKE the land first.
  |ref tabularium/terrestris.ordinum.udon (phase[protogenic] charge[smooth-water-surface]; phase[abyssal] charge[emergent-land] :tag gate, charge[erosion-carving] :tag gate) · nomotheke.rs SPINE.relation · examples/sea_level_probe.rs

|decision[check-the-ladder-not-modern-earth] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic process
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  STANDING GUARD. When interpreting a measurement about the world's state, check WHICH PHASE the ordinum says the world is in before deciding whether the result is a bug. Reasoning from modern Earth is a plausible-prior trap.
  |reason
    Twice in one day Claude took a CORRECT measurement and drew a WRONG conclusion from a plausible frame instead of the authoritative source: (1) `seam_ridge`'s 22888 (a divide-by-zero, believed because it confirmed the expected story); (2) the sea-level probe's water-world (declared "a hard coherence requirement — the world cannot exist", when the ordinum says a water-covered surface IS the Phase-1 promise and land is FORBIDDEN as an initial condition). Both times the disconfirming evidence was already written down and already read — in the probe's own output, and in the spine's own nomos declaration. The failure is not measurement; it is FRAMING.
  |impact
    Before calling a world-state result a defect: read the ordinum phase, read the nomos's own `relation`/`status` declaration, and ask what the ladder SAYS should be true at this phase. The declarations are the authority; modern Earth is not.

|decision[ordinum-governs-the-flux-web] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  THE ORDINUM'S PROMISES *ARE* FLUX QUANTITIES and `:kept-by` *IS* the producer. A nomos consuming an unkept promise is an UNMET need, so a world depending on it is mechanically UNRUNNABLE. The ladder governs the web — no new machinery, it just was never wired in.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "I was under the impression that the ordinum would literally be driving which nomos are even possible to add to the flux web — that it would be impossible to deviate from its constraints without essentially making it an unrunnable world." He was right, and wiring it exposed three things. (1) **My "closed flux web" was a LIE** — it printed "unmet flux needs: none" over a world that physically cannot run erosion, because erosion never DECLARED it needs LAND (it consumes `surface elevation`, which exists; not `emerged land`, which does not). Declared now → the audit convicts the world loudly, instead of erosion silently no-op'ing on seabed. (2) **The ladder was claiming coverage the registry lacked**: a BrokenKeeper check (`:kept-by` naming a nomos the nomotheke does not have) caught TWO undeclared nomos on its first two runs — `planet` (real insolation geometry keeping Phase-1 promise[axial-rhythms]) and `noise` (the KRNG keeping Phase-2 promise[seeded-asymmetry]). (3) **The initial-topography is no longer the root** — it consumes `seeded asymmetry` from `noise`, so the world's one acknowledged fundamental cheat (fBm-as-tectonics) is now an EDGE IN THE WEB rather than a secret inside a kernel.
  |impact
    `ordinum.rs` parses the tabularium artifact and computes each promise's MATURITY (NotStarted / Specified / Claimed / BrokenKeeper), enforcing the acceptance-test rule (no predicate ⇒ cannot be called fulfilled at any level). `Kept` is deliberately NOT auto-derived — the predicates are prose, and claiming Kept without running something that could refute it is exactly the plausibility-as-verification failure. **THE LADDER'S VERDICT ON WHAT TO BUILD NEXT, no longer a matter of taste: Abyssal `promise[emerged-land]` is SPECIFIED (falsifiable predicate) but NOTHING KEEPS IT — a `:tag gate`, the #1 gap, and the `uplift` nomos built today is exactly the piece that must deliver it.** STILL OWED: the maturity report is not wired into the CLI — the "which promises/charges are in-progress vs not-started" view Joseph actually asked to SEE. Engine exists; display does not.
  |ref ordinum.rs · nomotheke.rs (PLANET, NOISE) · flux.rs (EMERGED_LAND, SEEDED_ASYMMETRY, INSOLATION) · audit.rs

|decision[initial-topography-rename-executed] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic naming
  :supersedes initial-topography-name-holds
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  DONE. `spine` → `initial-topography` swept through all code (nomos name, static, query methods, `gen::initial_topography_m`, all callers). 87/87 green.
  |reason
    Decided this morning on the LEM literature (the standard term, immediately legible to geomorphologists; "spine" was an invented metaphor Joseph could not read geologically) — and then Claude spent the entire day writing NEW code that said "spine", until Joseph asked "what's the spine again?". A decided-but-unswept rename is a decision that keeps costing. **Lesson: sweep a naming decision the day it is made, or it propagates faster than it is fixed.**
  |impact
    Nomos name change re-keys its memos (cheap recompute). Ordinum resonance still owed: phase-0 ante-mundane's surface Promise should gain `:kept-by initial-topography`, and its water promise `:kept-by hydrosphere`.

|decision[seam-amortization-and-the-two-grid-overlay] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic physics
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  The topological charge can be AMORTIZED (physics) but not REMOVED (topology). Full reasoning — including the cube∪octahedron → cuboctahedron derivation and the rhombic-dodecahedral lead — is recorded in `ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md` §Addendum A1–A4, and MUST be incorporated into the pending grid-comparison report.
  |reason
    Joseph's intuition ("some way to do partial fluxes so that by the time you get to the worst area it's still 8 minus a little") is CORRECT. Conservation and routing do not depend on valence — flux is a boundary integral, and gradient-projected edge-flux routing (D-∞ on a mesh) fans outflow across however many edges exist as partial fluxes summing exactly. So the defect DEMOTES from a global conservation failure to a bounded local accuracy wart at 24 cells (LSQ gradients recover second order at any valence). **That is the argument that decides the grid does not need replacing.** The cube∪octahedron partition (Voronoi = cuboctahedron — Joseph guessed it before the derivation) is elegant and never evaluates a cell at a singularity, but it is an O(1)→O(N) trade and is recommended against — while its partial-edge MECHANISM is exactly right for the coarse↔fine tile seam, which is unavoidable and non-matching by nature.
  |ref ref/research/seam-adjacency-findings.md §Addendum · examples/grid_lab.rs · Snyder 1992 Table 1
